The relationships of the ratiometric fluorescent value (F515/F404) and UV absorbance rate of Fan,N-CDs with new coccine concentration were illustrated. The ratiometric fluorescent value of Fan,N-CDs decreased with new coccine concentration increasing (Fig. 6
                        a). The ratiometric fluorescent value of Fan,N-CDs was linear with new coccine concentrations (0–12.5 μM, R2 = 0.9911; 20–55 μM, R2 = 0.9902), with the low detection limit (LOD) of 30.12 nM and 54.85 nm, respectively (Fig. 6b). The UV absorption rate of Fan,N-CDs increased with new coccine concentration (Fig. 6c). The ratio of UV absorption of the Fan,N-CDs was linear with new coccine concentrations (0–45 μM, R2 = 0.9986), with LOD of 1.98 nM (Fig. 6d). It can be seen that the sensitivity is not the best, but the ratiometric fluorescent method has a wide detection range [30–37] (Table 1
                        ). Until now, there are no reports of green ratiometric fluorescent probe detection of new coccine. Ratiometric fluorescent probes can reduce background interference and show more widespread applications. Studies on the adsorption and removal of new coccine also have been reported [38–40].
